chrome.notes: Before Chrome 19, `click()` is only defined on buttons and inputs.

notes: Before Firefox 5, `click()` is only defined on buttons and inputs, and has no effect on text and file inputs.
Starting in Firefox 75, the `click()` function works even when the element is not attached to a DOM tree.
Before Firefox 5, `click()` is only defined on buttons and inputs, and has no effect on text and file inputs.
Starting in Firefox for Android 79, the `click()` function works even when the element is not attached to a DOM tree.

safari_ios.notes: If there's no hardware keyboard connected and the user has not yet interacted with the page, then calling `focus()` on an `<input>` element has no effect (for example, the element does not match the `:focus` selector).

__compat.description: Element is ignored for the purposes of find-in-page.
Requires `TrustedScript` instance in `HTMLScriptElement` when trusted types are enforced.

safari.notes: The property is defined only for its useful elements: `<link>`, `<script>`, and `<style>`; it is undefined for all other elements.

safari_ios.notes: On iOS and iPadOS, popovers are not dismissed when the user taps outside of the popover area, see [bug 267688](https://webkit.org/b/267688).

chrome.notes: When using this option, the focus order doesn't change, so the popover does not become the next focus element. See [bug 383343310](https://crbug.com/383343310).

safari.notes: When using this option, the focus order doesn't change, so the popover does not become the next focus element. See [bug 286575](https://webkit.org/b/286575).
